Blog posts support Docusaurus Markdown features, such as MDX. tip Use the power of React to create interactive blog posts. <button onClick={() => alert('button clicked!')}>Click me!</button> Click me!

Docusaurus blogging features are powered by the blog plugin. Simply add Markdown files (or folders) to the blog directory. Regular blog authors can be added to authors.yml. The blog post date can be extracted from filenames, such as: 2019-05-30-welcome.md 2019-05-30-welcome/index.md A blog post folder can be convenient to co-locate blog post images: The blog supports tags as well! And if you don't want a blog: just delete this directory, and use blog: false in your Docusaurus config.

Encryption technology is generally used when storing sensitive information in a database. For example, field encryption can be used to prevent data breaches of passwords required for login functionality.

After creating the Entity class, input the login-related attributes. @Getter @Setter @NoArgsConstructor public class Bar extends StageEntity { // public enum BarField { name, userId, password } private String name; private String userId; @FieldEncrypted private String password; ... To prevent sentitive data breaches of password attribute, the "@FieldEncrypted" annotation has been added. After completing all attributes and settings, use the automation feature to create the modifyAttributes() method and an internal Enum that lists the fields. Also enter the attributes to BarCdo class as well. Use â€˜Gen the field enumâ€™ to create inner Enum. public class Bar extends StageEntity { // public enum BarField { name, userId, password } ... In contrast, bar.setPassword(ValueEncryptor.decrypt(this.password)); retrieves the encrypted password information stored in the database, decrypts it back into its original password form, and sets it to the Entity field.

The Lingo service in the Vizend platform handles multilingual label management across applications using the @vizendjs/vizend-layout package. To use Lingo, your application should follow this flow: Manage Labels Set User Language Fetch and Store Labels in Local Storage Use Accent Util for Label Transformation ğŸ’¬ These steps correspond to a full cycle of multilingual handling in the Vizend platform. Each step should be correctly placed in the app lifecycle for full functionality.
To use the Lingo service, you must include the following dependency: { "dependencies": { "@vizendjs/vizend-layout": "7.0.14-35" } } âœ¨ Make sure to use version 7.0.14-35 or higher for compatibility.
Label management happens via the Metro Lingo Configuration page, where users define keys and multilingual values for each Kollex.

KollexLabelâ€‹ The core domain for label definitions: public class KollexLabel extends StageEntity { private String labelKey; private Map<String, String> langLabels; private String kollexId; private String pavilionId; } KollexLangLabelâ€‹ Used for queries in the list view, tied to specific languages. public class KollexLangLabel extends StageEntity implements QueryModel { private String labelKey; private String langCode; private String langLabel; private String kollexId; private String kollexLabelId; private String pavilionId; } BaseLabelâ€‹ Fallback labels shared across Kollexes. public class BaseLabel extends StageEntity { private String labelKey; private Map<String, String> langLabels; private String pavilionId; } LabelBookâ€‹ Maintains ID sequences for other label domains: public class LabelBook extends StageEntity { private int baseLabelSequence; private int kollexLabelSequence; } ğŸŒ Each Pavilion (company) is assigned a single LabelBook to generate consistent IDs across labels.

If a matching BaseLabel exists, it auto-fills values. ğŸš€Steps: Select a Kollex Enter the label key Click â€œFind Baseâ€ to auto-fill translations (optional) Modify or complete translations and click Confirm Bulk Add: Upload multiple labels via CSV or JSON files. ğŸš€ Steps: Choose a data format (CSV/JSON) Select the Kollex Upload file or paste formatted data Click Confirm âœï¸ Edit Labelsâ€‹ Click a label row to open the side panel. You can: Auto-fill from BaseLabel Modify and save translations ğŸ“˜ Use the â€œFind Baseâ€ option here as well for existing keys. ğŸ—‘ï¸ Delete Labelsâ€‹ Click the trash icon on a label row to delete. ğŸ“˜ This action removes the associated KollexLabel.

Set the user's language using LocalStorage on app load: useEffect(() => { const language = localStorage.getItem("vizend.language"); if (!language) { localStorage.setItem("vizend.language", "english"); } }, []); Update language on user change: const changeLanguage = (language: string) => { localStorage.setItem('vizend.language', language); window.location.reload(); }; ğŸ“˜ Be sure to force a page refresh, as language changes in localStorage are not detected automatically.

Use initializeI18nResource() from @vizendjs/lingo-view in your shared layout: const { initializeI18nResource } = useLingo(context); const [loadLanguage, setLoadLanguage] = useState(false); useEffect(() => { if (!!context) { initializeI18nResource().finally(() => setLoadLanguage(true)); } }, [context]); return loadLanguage && <YourComponent />; ğŸ“˜ This is typically done in a layout file like DefaultLayout.tsx that wraps your app.

Use l() to translate label keys: import { l } from "@vizendjs/accent"; l('Hi'); // "ì•ˆë…•" l('Hello, my name is {name}.', {name: 'ë„¥ìŠ¤íŠ¸ë¦¬'}); l('LoremIpsumDolor'); // returns "LoremIpsumDolor" if key not found If: No language set Label not found Key not registered Then it returns the key as-is.

No React hooks (stateless) Requires manual refresh on language change No component-based rendering (\n â†”
not supported) No missing-key notifications from Lingo ğŸ“˜ Because l() is in a non-React utility package (accent), context, useEffect, useState, etc., are not usable. This limits dynamic capabilities.

The Lingo service streamlines multilingual label handling with flexible tools for setup, configuration, and real-time translation. For best results: Ensure dependencies are set Load dictionary at app start Use l() for dynamic translation ğŸ“˜ For scalability, use the Metro Lingo Config page for centralized management and track missing keys through BaseLabel alignment strategies.

Menu bar -> File -> New -> Project -> Select â€˜Vizend Studioâ€™ from the left menu of the dialogue box -> choose Drama Backend for Project Style -> After selecting the remaining options, click Next button. The options are divided into five sections: Project Style, Project Template, Store Type, Drama Information, and Build Method. Choose one of the project style from options based on your need. CQRS has been configured within the project template. CQRS stands for Command Query Responsibility Segregation, is a design pattern that separates the responsibilities of handling commands and queries in a Java program, optimizing read and write operations independently for separate handling. This includes synchronizing the application state between different components by using events. If you check theâ€™ Add Mashup moduleâ€™ option, the Mashup module will be created along with other modules. If you check the â€˜Skip Event Generationâ€™ option, event code will not be generated. You can choose from a variety of databases such as MongoDB, MariaDB, and Oracle. In the Drama Information section, you can input the Group ID and Module Prefix. The Group ID determines the group of the drama and the packageâ€™s name. You can change the project module name with the Module Prefix. Only Gradle is available for the Build Method option. After selecting all the options, click Next button. Enter the project name and choose the project location in the following window. According to the Drama naming rule, words should be lowercase letters and separated by hyphen '-'. (Special characters are not allowed.) If there is no Module Prefix, the word entered after '-' will be used as the project module name. You can also enter a single word without using '-'. After entering the Project namd and location, click Create button. The directory name and module name may vary based on the project name and prefix you entered. The default module name is based on the project name. In other words, it will be represented by the word entered after '-' in the project name. (If '-' is not entered, it will be represented as a single word.) The module name is based on the additional prefix input. "If '-' is entered more than once, all words following each '-' will be considered part of the module name. Click â€œLoad Gradle Projectâ€ button on the bottom right of the project to allow the Gradle build script to load. If you can not Load Gradle successfully, go to Project Structure to change the version of SDK version and Settings to change the Gradle JVM version. Menu bar -> File -> Project Structure -> Project -> SDK Find the version of SDK 21 from options. If thereâ€™s no SDK21, click Download JDK. Choose the Version and Vendor to Version 21, and click Download button. Back to the Project Structure, choose the version21 and click OK button. The Gradle JVM version should also be changed to version 21. Menu bar -> File -> Settings -> Build -> Gradle Choose Gradle JVM to version21 and Click OK button. After setting up the SDK version 21, click the â€œReloadâ€ button. Reload completed successfully.

build.gradle file The build.gradle file contains information related to the module versions and dependencies used. BootApplication file Under the boot module, the BootApplication is also generated. MongoTransactionConfig file The MongoTransactionConfig is also generated if you choose Mongodb as your database. schema file A script file for schema generation is also generated. The database needs to be configured based on the script file. application.yml file The application.yml file required for boot execution is also generated. Role file In the facade module, a â€˜Roleâ€™ class is generated, which is used to define drama roles. If additional drama roles are needed, developers can add them to this class.

Menu bar -> File -> New -> Project -> Select â€˜Vizend Studioâ€™ from the left menu of the dialogue box -> choose Drama Frontend for Project Style. Select the options you need and click Next button. The frontend project name should be appended with '-front' following the backend project name. This is because the Studio generates frontend code based on the backend code, and the Studio needs to place the generated frontend code into the frontend project. By default, it looks for a project named '[Backend project name]-front'. After entering the Project namd and location, click Create button. The Frontend Project has been generated.

editorconfig file .editorconfig file is a text editor configuration file used for maintaining consistent coding styles across different editors and IDEs. eslintignore file .eslintignore file is for specifying directories in ESLint. eslintrc file .eslintrc file defines the syntax and style of JavaScript code. gitignore file .gitignore file specifies the list of files to be excluded from Git version management. gitlab-ci.yml file GitLab CI/CD pipeline configuration file used to define automated build, test, and deployment pipelines for your project. npmrc file npm configuration file used to configure npm behavior and settings, which control the operation for npm package administrator. prettierignore file This is the file used to specify directories for Prettier. prettierrc file This is the Prettier configuration file, containing settings that define the formatting of the code. package.json file The package.json file contains information about the environment and modules required for Frontend development. README.md file Markdown file containing documentation for your project, including usage instructions, installation guidelines, project overview, and any other relevant information. tsconfig.json file The tsconfig.json file contains options information for TypeScript compilation. turbo.json file Configuration file used by Turbo framework, if applicable, to specify project settings like build configurations, environment variables, and runtime options. You can also create a Frontend Project within a Backend Project. Project vizend-foo -> quick right click -> Vizend Studio -> Click 'Change Front Project...' If a Frontend project already exists, select 'Use Default Location' and click OK button. If a Frontend project does not exist and another specified Frontend project exists, uncheck 'Use Default Location' and select the other Frontend project. Select the other Frontend project and click the Open button. After selecting the specified file, click OK button. If a Frontend project does not exist and 'Use Default Location' is selected, click OK button will pop up the window asking whether to create a Frontend project. Click Yes button to create Default Front Project. Click OK button, you can find the Frontend Project at the specified location you choose.
This document is intended to provide an overview of how to use Studio for those who are new to Studio, and to get started with Drama development quickly.

Search â€œVizend Studioâ€ from the following menu and install. Menu bar -> File -> Settings -> Plugins -> Marketplace -> vizend search In the search results, select the "Install" button for Vizend Studio to proceed with the installation. Once the installation is complete, restart the IntelliJ IDE.

Menu bar -> File -> New -> Project -> Select "Vizend Studio" from the menu on the left-hand side of the dialog box Select the options you need and click Next button. To manually set the module name for your project, enter the name in the "Module Prefix" field. If left blank, the module name will be automatically generated. Select the "Project Location" and follow the Drama naming rules (for example, use lowercase and hyphens(-) only, avoid special characters) when entering the project name in the "Project name" field. Then click Create button. The entered Project name is used to create the project module name. If you do not enter a Module Prefix, this is how the created project will appear. If you enter 'demo' as the Module Prefix, this is how the project will appear. Click â€œLoad Gradle Projectâ€ button on the bottom right of the project to allow the Gradle build script to load. If you can not Load Gradle successfully, go to Project Structure to change the version of SDK version and Settings to change the Gradle JVM version to 21. Menu bar -> File -> Project Structure -> Project -> SDK Find the version of SDK 21, if thereâ€™s no SDK21, click Download JDK Choose the Version and Vendor to Version 21, and click Download button. Back to the Project Structure, choose the version21 and click OK button. Menu bar -> File -> Settings -> Build -> Gradle Choose Gradle JVM to version21 and Click OK button. After setting up the SDK version 21, click â€œLoad Gradle Projectâ€ button to reload.

Select the Project tree from the left menu -> foo-aggregate -> quick right click -> Vizend Studio -> Click â€˜Create Aggregate entity and Cdoâ€¦â€™ Choose the Entity type, enter Aggregate Name, and Entity Name in the dialog box, then click OK button. Bar Entity and BarCdo Class will be created in individually. You can also create 'Gen the field enum' to define the names of the fields as an internal enum. Back to the Project Tree -> Select Bar Entity -> quick right click -> Vizend Studio -> Click â€˜Create Backend Codesâ€¦â€™ Select â€œCreate All Codesâ€ in the dialog box and click OK button to generate all backend codes. The dialog box displaying the creation result shows the number of generated files and the status of the created codes. The 'Command', 'Query', 'Domain', and 'Store' codes within the selected Entity have been generated as shown in the following Project Tree. If additional methods are needed beyond those provided by the automatically generated Store interface, you can use the "OptionStore interface". The naming of additional methods can follow the Derived Query Methods of Spring Data.

Itâ€™s also EASY to create a NEW Feature code to your Drama project. Enter Feature Name / Sub-Feature Name to distinguish the difference in categories. Click OK button to generate Feature Codes. package io.vizend.foo.facade.feature.foo.bar.command; ... @Getter @Setter @AllArgsConstructor @NoArgsConstructor @AuthorizedRole(FooRole.Director) public class RegisterActiveBarCommand extends CommandRequest { public void validate() { /** * FIXME : User Implementation * Example. * Assert.hasText(skuNo, "'skuNo' is required"); * Assert.isTrue(increaseRate > 0, "'increaseRate' is greater than 0"); */ } ... This is the generated FeatureRequest class. The 'foo' and 'bar' preceding the package name 'command' represent the feature and sub-feature names, respectively. Enter the feature attributes and revise the content of the validate() method if necessary. Back to the Project tree ->Select the RegisterActiveBarCommand (CommandRequest Class) -> quick right click -> Vizend Studio -> Click â€˜Create Feature Codesâ€¦â€™ The Flow Name is basically the one you enter the Feature name and Flow/Seek Logic Name from the previous process. Flow Name can be modified if you need a different one. Click OK button to create Flow Class. The â€˜FlowFacadeâ€™, â€˜FlowResourceâ€™ and â€˜Flowâ€™ codes have been generated. Here's a snippet of the generated code for FooBarFlow class. Developers can add/revise Flow codes here if necessary.

Now Generate the Frontend Code based on the backend code youâ€™ve worked on so far. Back to the Project Tree -> Select the vizend-foo -> quick right click -> Vizend Studio -> Click â€˜Create All Frontend Codesâ€¦â€™ This dialog indicates that the frontend project location has not been created or specified yet. If you want to use the default location from the project, check the 'Use Default Location' box and click OK button. Click Yes button to create Frontend Project. Frontend Project has been created and click OK button to continue. Select the backend files as the basis for creation on the left side of the dialog box, and choose the creation target on the right side of the dialog box. The dialog box shows the result of generated codes, click OK button to view generated codes. Open the â€œdrama-foo-front projectâ€ in new window from the Default location to view the generated frontend codes.

To directly define the identity of an Entity, you can use VoidEntity in Studio. The identity used in existing DomainEntity and StageEntity will be managed within the platform.

Select the menu for creating an Entity, and choose VoidEntity as the Entity type from the following dialogue box. @Getter @Setter @NoArgsConstructor public class Foo extends VoidEntity { public Foo(String id) { // TODO : Set the id to your own value } public Foo(FooCdo fooCdo) { super(); BeanUtils.copyProperties(fooCdo, this); } @Override public String getId() { // TODO : Get the id from your own value return null; } ... Here's a snippet of the generated code for VoidEntity. Developers need to implement the constructor and the internals of the get method to exchange identity with other platform codes such as Logic or Event. @Getter @Setter @NoArgsConstructor public class Foo extends VoidEntity { @FieldId private String myFooId; private String name; public Foo(String id) { this.myFooId = id; } public Foo(FooCdo fooCdo) { super(); BeanUtils.copyProperties(fooCdo, this); } @Override public String getId() { return myFooId; } ... In the above code, myFooId is the entity ID. To inform Studio that myFooId is an ID, we add the '@FieldId' annotation. Then, we implement the constructor and getId method. After that, select the Foo entity to generate all other codes. Since the identity is located in the Foo entity, the generated code will be slightly different from StageEntity and DomainEntity. @Getter @Setter @NoArgsConstructor @Entity @Table(name = "FOO") public class FooJpo implements JsonSerializable { /* Gen by Vizend Studio v5.1.0 */ @Id private String myFooId; private String name; public FooJpo(Foo foo) { /* Gen by Vizend Studio v5.1.0 */ BeanUtils.copyProperties(foo, this); } public Foo toDomain() { /* Gen by Vizend Studio v5.1.0 */ Foo foo = new Foo(); BeanUtils.copyProperties(this, foo); return foo; } ... In the generated JPO, the '@Id' annotation has been applied to myFooId. Additionally, the constructor and toDomain method code in the JPO differs from that of the existing DomainEntity's JPO. Vizend Studio provides a feature to generate Entity and CDO using YAML format files. This document aims to describe the methods for writing YAML documents.
groupId: io.vizend appName: small-talk groupId and appName are essential inputs that influence the package naming during code generation.

entities: - name: RoomBoard type: Stage aggregate: room Below the "entities" section, input a list of items. Input the name and type(available types are Stage, Domain, Data, Void). Input the name of aggregate. This is a mandatory field and influences the determination of the Entity package during generation.
The method for entering attribute information is applied not only for Entity but also for ValueObject and ValueGroup.

entities: - name: Address type: Stage aggregate: address attributes: - name: city type: String comment: ë„ì‹œ example: Seoul Below the "attributes" section, input a list of items. Input the name. If not provided, it will generate the attribute based on the type name. Input the "type", which can be a primitive type or a Java type name. If not provided, it will be considered as String. If you input a "comment", it will generate a field annotation. If you input an "example", it will be used for generating sample() method code.

1. Input name onlyâ€‹ attributes: - name: question You can only specify the 'name' attribute. In this case, it will generate an attribute named 'question' with a String type. private String question; 2. Input name and typeâ€‹ attributes: - name: time type: long The most common method is to specify 'name' and 'type'. 'Type' can include not only primitive types but also Java class name. private long time; 3. Usage of list attributesâ€‹ attributes: - name: usages list: io.vizend.accent.domain.xray.usage.FeatureUsage If the attribute type is List, you can define the generic type. In this case, the code will be generated as following. If 'name' is omitted, the attribute name will be determined by the type name defined in the list. private List<FeatureUsage> usages; 4. immutableâ€‹ attributes: - name: time type: long immutable: true If you set the 'immutable' attribute to true, the generated entity attributes will include the '@FieldImmutable' annotation, creating immutable attributes that cannot be modified. @FieldImmutable private long time;
Entity code is generated based on the relation between entities. You can define 1:N and 1:1 relation using three attributes: oneToMany, manyToOne, and oneToOne.

If there is a one-to-many relationship between the two defined entities, you can use the 'oneToMany' and 'manyToOne' attributes. The following example illustrates the case where RoomBoard and RoomieBoard have a 1:N relation. Configuration for the One side Entity entities: - name: RoomBoard ... oneToMany: entity: RoomieBoard Configuration for the Many side Entity - name: RoomieBoard ... manyToOne: entity: RoomBoard Entity Code Generated from the Above Configuration. Code for the One side Entity public class RoomBoard extends StageEntity { ... private transient List<RoomieBoard> roomieBoards; ... Code for the Many side Entity public class RoomieBoard extends StageEntity { ... @FieldSourceId private String roomBoardId; ... In the above code, the One side Entity can conceptually have the Many side Entity objects in a List format. However, since it doesn't actually hold the objects, the corresponding field is generated as transient. The Many side Entity can have a reference to the One side, so a field of type FieldSourceId is generated.

When the relation between two entities is one-to-one, you can define the relation using the 'oneToOne' attribute. In this case, you can declare ownership under the 'owning' sub-attribute in one of the entities. Configuration for the One (Owning) side Entity - name: Roomie ... oneToOne: entity: RoomieBoard owning: true Configuration for the One (Not Owning) side Entity - name: RoomieBoard ... oneToOne: entity: Roomie Generated Entity Code. In the above code, on the owner side, the entity conceptually owns the related entity but doesn't actually own it, so it's declared as a transient field. Additionally, on the non-owning side, the entity holds the owner's entity ID in the form of FieldSourceId.
You can input the necessary information for ValueObject, ValueGroup, and Enum while defining the Entity. All three can be defined as attributes of the Entity or externally to the Entity.

Entity internal definition entities: - name: RoomBoard type: Stage aggregate: room attributes: ... - valueObject: name: LastTalk attributes: - name: roomId - name: name - name: message The method of internal definition in Entity is to define attributes of the Entity. You can define 'valueObject' or 'valueGroup' as a sublist item under 'attributes' and specify the name and attruibutes. In this case, if you doan't input an aggregate, it is generated under the aggregate defined in the parent Entity. Entity external definition valueObjects: - name: LastTalk aggregate: room attributes: - name: roomId - name: name - name: message You can define ValueObject/ValueGroup external of the Entity. They can be defined as sublist items under 'valueObjects' or 'valueGroups'. It's important to note that you must define an aggregate. The defined ValueObject or ValueGroup will be generated under the specified aggregate.
